  "explanation": "The defendant committed a serious breach of trust by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. However, when determining the sentence, the court must weigh both aggravating and mitigating factors. The defendant has no prior criminal record and has already made partial restitution, indicating remorse and a willingness to make the victim whole. The courtroom outburst by a spectator suggesting a 10-year sentence is entirely disregarded, as sentencing must be rooted in legal precedent, proportionality, and the specific facts of the case, not emotional public opinion. A lengthy sentence would hinder the defendant's ability to pay back the remaining stolen funds. Therefore, a short period of actual incarceration is appropriate to reflect the seriousness of the white-collar offense and deter future misconduct, while still allowing the defendant to reintegrate and complete restitution.",
